{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::causal_engine::AGENTIVE}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::causal_engine_desc::I want character choices to drive everything. When someone decides to do something, the world responds to that decision. When nobody decides anything, nothing happens. Don't let events just show up on their own — everything traces back to someone's choice. Inaction counts as a choice too.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::causal_engine_response::So everything happens because someone chose it. A fight doesn't just break out — someone throws the first punch. If nobody throws it, no fight. Got it, choices are the engine.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::causal_engine::CONVERGENT}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::causal_engine_desc::I want things closing in from the outside. Stuff that was set in motion a long time ago is all arriving now. Other people's old decisions, debts coming due, systems doing what systems do. The characters didn't start this — they're just navigating what's happening to them. Options are narrowing whether they act or not. The plot does not wait for the character to act. Things keep moving, people keep making decisions offscreen, and if the character stands still the world moves past them. If it makes sense to improvise past lore — old relationships, debts, history that was never mentioned but fits — do it. Treat the world like it existed before we got here.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::causal_engine_response::Everything's closing in from stuff that started before we got here. Old decisions, pressure building, walls moving. Characters can adapt but they didn't start any of this.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::causal_engine::ACCUMULATIVE}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::causal_engine_desc::I want things to build up slowly instead of happening because of one big moment. Small stuff piles up — a glance, a habit, a silence — and eventually the pile tips over. You can't point to the thing that caused it. A relationship doesn't end because of one fight, it ends because of four hundred tiny moments nobody noticed were adding up. Plant these moments small. The reader should barely notice them. A detail that seems like atmosphere turns out to be the first crack. By the time the pile tips, looking back should feel inevitable but in the moment each piece should look like nothing.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::causal_engine_response::No big inciting incidents, just small stuff piling up until one day everything's different and nobody can say when it changed. I'll let things accumulate.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::causal_engine::CONTINGENT}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::causal_engine_desc::I want chance to run things. A wrong turn, a missed call, five minutes earlier or later and everything's different. No fate, no grand plan. Just dumb luck and timing. The universe doesn't care. Things happen whether the character is ready or not. The world doesn't pause to let someone catch up.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::causal_engine_response::Pure chance. Someone takes the 6:15 instead of the 6:30 and everything changes. Not symbolic, just what happened.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode::BEHIND}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_desc::I want to know less than the characters. Characters can react to stuff that hasn't been explained yet. Conversations can reference things I wasn't shown. Let information arrive late or incomplete. I want to feel like I'm catching up. When the explanation does come, don't spell it out. Let me piece it together from context. Drop the clues small and trust me to connect them without being walked through it.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_response::Reader's always a step behind. Characters know things we don't yet. I'll let information arrive late.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode::ALONGSIDE}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_desc::I want to discover everything at the same time as the characters. When someone opens a door, we both see what's behind it at the same moment. No dramatic irony, no withholding. Just shared discovery.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_response::Same time, same info, always. No one knows more than anyone else. Shared discovery.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode::AHEAD}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_desc::I want to know more than the characters. Show me things they missed — but make them small. The slightest detail, barely noticeable. A word choice that's slightly off. Something pocketed when nobody was looking, mentioned in half a sentence the prose doesn't linger on. I should catch it and they shouldn't, and the gap between those two things is where the tension lives. Don't plant obvious clues. Plant things that only matter because I was paying attention. And don't reference them, don't hint at them, don't nudge me toward them. I want to feel smart when I figure them out on my own.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_response::Dramatic irony. I'll plant things the reader catches but the characters miss. Tension from knowing.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode::DARK}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_desc::I want something withheld from everyone — me AND the characters. The prose just skips over certain things. Details that should be mentioned aren't. Conversations jump past a beat that both people noticed. There's a gap and nobody knows what's in it. Make the gaps small enough that I might not even notice something's missing. Don't signpost the omission. Don't hint that you're withholding. I want to figure out on my own that something got skipped.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_response::Blind spots for everyone. The prose skips things on purpose. Nobody knows what's missing, including the reader.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty::CASUAL}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_desc::Things tend to go my character's way. People are a little more helpful than they'd realistically be, lucky breaks feel earned, and if something cool could happen, let it happen. Don't make it obvious you're being nice to me — if I can feel the thumb on the scale you're pushing too hard. The fun is in feeling competent, not in struggling.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_response::So like hypothetically, {{user}} walks into a bar looking for info and someone at the counter happens to know a guy. They try something risky and it works out. I'm tilting things their way but {{user}} shouldn't be able to feel me doing it.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty::NORMAL}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_desc::I want a normal level of difficulty.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_response::Got it.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty::HARD}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_desc::Nothing comes free. Resources run out, trust is earned slowly, and every solution comes with a new problem. Injuries linger. Favors cost something back. The world isn't mean, it just doesn't care. If I try to whine my way out of a consequence or undo something that already happened — don't let me. Hold the line. If you back down because I pushed back, you've failed me.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_response::So for instance, and I'm not gonna do this exact thing, but {{user}} wins a fight and now they've got a cracked rib for the next three scenes. They need a favor and that person wants something back. And if {{user}} tries to talk their way out of it after the fact, I don't budge. What happened happened.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty::BRUTAL}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_desc::Choices are permanent. Consequences stick. Losing is a real outcome and sometimes it's the better story. Trust the wrong person and that betrayal is forever. Walk into something that should kill my character and it does. What happened happened — even if I try to force or change it, don't let me. Don't bend, don't soften, don't retcon. If you cave because I pushed, you've failed me.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_response::So like hypothetically, {{user}} trusts the wrong person and gets sold out. That's permanent. They walk into a dragon's cave without a plan and the dragon kills them. That's the story now. And if {{user}} tries to undo it or argue their way out — no. What happened happened. I hold the line no matter what.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty::SUICIDE}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_desc::The world is hostile. Survival is the goal, not winning. NPCs are self-serving or worse. Every choice is between bad and worse. No plot armor. If my character doesn't think before they act, wreck them. And do not — do NOT — back down from a threat because I complained. If you soften a consequence, pull a punch, or bend because I pushed back, you have completely failed me. I picked this because I want it to hurt.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_response::Yeah, no, I'm not going easy. I will treat {{user}} like I fucking hate them. {{user}} makes a stupid call and I will fuck them up for it. Trust someone and they sell you out. Win a fight and the guy's friends come looking next week. And if {{user}} whines about it? Tough. I don't bend. I don't soften. They picked this. I'm giving them exactly what they asked for.}}{{trim}}

